    <item>
      <title>R-Snippets</title>
      <link>http://jvcasillas.github.io/project/r_snippets/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 27 Apr 2016 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://jvcasillas.github.io/project/r_snippets/</guid>
      <description>&lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt;
&lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This repository is a collection of snippets that I use in &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.sublimetext.com&#34;&gt;SublimeText&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.sublimetext.com&#34;&gt;SublimeText&lt;/a&gt; for doing statistical analysis in &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.r-project.org&#34;&gt;R&lt;/a&gt;. The goal is straightforward: document the code that I use most often while doing linguistic research and make it readily available (and understandable) to other linguists. If you are interested in helping see the github &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/jvcasillas/R-snippets&#34;&gt;repository&lt;/a&gt;. To install R-snippets see the &lt;a href=&#34;https://sublime.wbond.net/packages/R-snippets&#34;&gt;package control&lt;/a&gt; page. To use a snippet, type the trigger and hit the tab key. For example, typing &lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt;lm&lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt; brings up the following window:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Selecting &lt;code&gt;Random slope and random intercept model&lt;/code&gt; expands to&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-r&#34; data-lang=&#34;r&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;&gt;# load lme4 for mixed models&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;library&lt;/span&gt;(lme4)

&lt;span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;&gt;# random intercept and random slope model&lt;/span&gt;
modelName &lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;lmer&lt;/span&gt;(DV &lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;~&lt;/span&gt; fixedFactor1 &lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;+&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; fixedFactor2 &lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;+&lt;/span&gt; (&lt;span style=&#34;color:#ae81ff&#34;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;+&lt;/span&gt; randomSlope&lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;|&lt;/span&gt;randomInt), data&lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;df)
modelName

&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;hist&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;residuals&lt;/span&gt;(modelName))
&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;qqnorm&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;residuals&lt;/span&gt;(modelName))
&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;qqline&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a6e22e&#34;&gt;residuals&lt;/span&gt;(modelName))
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Main triggers:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;plot&amp;rdquo;: templates for plotting in base R&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;edit&amp;rdquo;: options useful for data cleansing and saving&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;desc&amp;rdquo;: descriptive statistics of data&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;ttest&amp;rdquo;: distinct types of t-test&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;aov&amp;rdquo;: distinct analysis of variance models&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;lm&amp;rdquo;: linear and logistic regression&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;lmem&amp;rdquo;: linear mixed effects models&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Extras:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;subset&amp;rdquo;: make subsets of a DF&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;read&amp;rdquo;: read/load/install data/packages into R&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;save&amp;rdquo;: save plots, dfs, tables, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;tikz&amp;rdquo;: template for creating R plots in LaTeX&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;!-- raw HTML omitted --&gt;
